Abstract

The integration of Artificial Intelligence (AI) into safety‑critical automotive systems presents a fundamental challenge: ISO 26262, the international standard for functional safety in road vehicles, was designed for deterministic systems with predictable, bounded behavior. Stochastic AI models — by their probabilistic nature — cannot be certified under the existing framework. This paper introduces ST‑T1024, an open standard (Apache 2.0) for deterministic embedded AI inference that replaces stochastic transformer inference with a fully deterministic, Finite State Machine (FSM)‑orchestrated, ternary‑quantized pipeline. We demonstrate how ST‑T1024's architecture inherently satisfies ISO 26262 requirements for determinism, traceability, freedom from interference, and ASIL decomposition, positioning it as the first AI inference architecture that is certifiable under existing functional safety standards without requiring standard amendments. With a worst‑case execution time of ≤800 ns, 99.9% energy reduction versus cloud‑based inference, and zero‑hallucination operation, ST‑T1024 offers a practical path toward certifiable AI in automotive, aerospace, and industrial safety‑critical systems.

Keywords — ISO 26262, functional safety, deterministic AI, embedded systems, ASIL, RISC‑V, FSM, ternary quantization, safety‑critical systems, automotive AI

