3. ST‑T1024 Architecture — Deterministic by Design

ST‑T1024 replaces stochastic inference with a deterministic pipeline:

Layer Component ISO 26262 Relevance
Triage Fuzzy Inference System (FIS) Bounded routing — no probabilistic branching
Scheduling Finite State Machine (FSM) WCET enforcement — predictable execution
Execution Ternary logic {-1, 0, +1} No floating‑point — deterministic quantization
Isolation Tile‑based architecture Freedom from interference — ASIL decomposition ready
Power 0V gating Predictable energy — no thermal variance

3.1 Determinism

ST‑T1024 enforces determinism at every level:

· Temperature = 0.0 — no stochastic sampling
· FSM cycle counter — WCET ≤ 800 ns
· Ternary arithmetic — no floating‑point variance
· Fixed memory layout — 75% ROM, 25% SRAM

3.2 Traceability

Every decision is auditable:

· FSM state transitions are logged
· FIS routing is deterministic
· Outputs are either truth or 0x‑AMBIG — no confabulation

3.3 Freedom from Interference

ST‑T1024 uses N independent domain tiles. Only one tile activates per query; all others are gated to 0V. This eliminates resource contention and ensures that a failure in one tile cannot propagate to others — a prerequisite for ASIL decomposition.

3.4 ASIL Decomposition

ISO 26262 allows ASIL decomposition when independent safety mechanisms are used. ST‑T1024's tile‑based architecture enables:

· Low ASIL perception units — each tile handles a specific domain
· High ASIL monitor unit — the FSM supervises all transitions
· Algorithm diversification — different tiles can use different logic

